\begin_layout BeginFrame
Types of Source Control.
\end_layout

\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

For k 'andles.
 Handles for Forks.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Generally come in one or two forms
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Pause

\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Centralised
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Rely on a single central repository, from which everyone 'pulls' from and
 'pushes' to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The one TRUE repository...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
[Image to go here]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some examples:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
RCS - http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revision_Control_System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CVS - http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concurrent_Versions_System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subversion (SVN) - http://subversion.apache.org/
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Pause

\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Distributed
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Doesn't necessarily rely on a single central repository
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Peer to peer in a sense, everyone has a 
\shape italic
bona fide
\shape default
 repository
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sets of changes are shared between 'peers'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
[Image to go here]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some examples:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Bazaar - http://bazaar.canonical.com/
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mercurial - http://mercurial.selenic.com/
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Git - http://git-scm.com/
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout BeginFrame
Centralised vs Distributed
\end_layout

\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
(Donning flameproof pants....) 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Sides? Whadya mean I gotta choose sides!?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve different problems, may as well compare apples to oranges
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Pause

\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Centralised
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
'
\shape italic
One True Source
\shape default
' which is blessed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Developers work on a local copy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Changes become blessed once 'pushed' up and merged
\end_layout

\begin_layout Pause

\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Distributed
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
No one repository is blessed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In practice, there may be a few repositories that have ultimate trust
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But this is defined by either the workflow process used, or based on a web
 of trust, i.e., historical merit or quality of changes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Pause

\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The real choice is purely organisational, or workflow based
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Centralised - only ever one internal team (there may even by limited external
 access e.g.
 via vpn)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Distributed - geographically seperated developers
\end_layout

\end_deeper
